%text If $z = y-x$ then % \begin{align}
\frac{dz}{z^2-1} = dx &\implies \int \frac{dz}{z^2-1} = \int dx \\ \text{or } x &= \frac{1}{2}\log\left\vert \frac{y-x-1}{y-x+1}\right\vert + C \end{align} %text But as $y = 0$ when $x=0$, therefore $C = 0$. Hence, \[ \quad \underbrace{y = e^{2x}\cdot \left(y-x+1 \right) + (x+1)}_{\text{Answer}}\]
